Regulation of longevity by the reproductive system.

Antebi A(1).

Author information:
(1)Max Planck Institute for Biology of Ageing, Gleueler Str. 50a, D-50931 
Cologne, Germany. AAntebi@age.mpg.de

Pioneering work in model organisms reveals that the reproductive system is 
involved not only in propagation of the species but also regulates organismal 
metabolism and longevity. In C. elegans, prevention of germline stem cell 
proliferation results in a 60% extension of lifespan, termed gonadal longevity. 
Gonadal longevity relies on the transcriptional activities of steroid nuclear 
receptor DAF-12, the FOXO transcription factor homolog DAF-16, the FOXA 
transcription factor homolog PHA-4, and the HNF-4-like nuclear receptor NHR-80. 
These transcription factors work in an integrated transcriptional network to 
regulate fatty acid lipolysis, autophagy, stress resistance and other processes, 
which altogether enhance homeostasis and extend life. Because the reproductive 
system also regulates longevity in other species, studies in C. elegans may shed 
light on ancient mechanisms governing reproduction and survival.

